description: From Middle English medlen, from Anglo-Norman medler, from early Medieval Latin misculāre, derived from Latin misceō (“to mix”).

verbs.description: meddle (third-person singular simple present meddles, present participle meddling, simple past and past participle meddled)

entries.meaning: To interfere in or with; to concern oneself with unduly. [from 14thc.]
examples: Synonyms: dabble, stick one's nose into, stick one's oar in

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To interest or engage oneself; to have to do (with), in a good sense.
(obsolete) To mix (something) with some other substance; to commingle, combine, blend. [14th–17th c.]
examples: Synonyms: bemingle, combine, ming; see also Thesaurus:mix

entries.meaning: (intransitive, now US regional) To have sex. [from 14thc.]
examples: Synonyms: do it, get it on, ming; see also Thesaurus:copulate
